column2: product__v.external_id__v is getting truncated
column10:
Customer: MSD, Job ID: 4aa9cb75-6025-4be2-8

External IDs on Product_vod__c are up to 38 characters for MSD US. Migrator is currently truncating the values to 25 characters which causes some values to become duplicates of each other. This is causing products to fail and cascading to millions of transactional failures.

column2: Events held in last 2 years should not be filtered out if created > 2 years ago

column2: record_type__v historical values
column10:
For objects that have the record_type__v field, such as Suggestions, historical values come over with '_vod" whereas new values are created with '__v'. This discrepancy is creating issues for DSI's X-Page dev as they need to account for both record_type__v values in their queries. They also can't use object_type__vr.api_name__v as field relationships are not supported in X-Page queries and the getObjecTypes() method (https://developer.veevacrm.com/doc/Content/CRM_topics/Vault/x-pages-library.htm#getObjectTypesobjectincludeInactive) is not available in Studio.

Example:
-Object: suggestion__v
-migrated record: id = VBYZ04ASG4BRIWX --> record_type_name__v = Call_vod
-new record after migration: id = VBY000000002783 --> record_type_name__v = call__v

The request is to have migrator update all record_type_name__v values to the new vault naming convention
column12: X-page development, the workaround is to include both legacy and new record_type__v values

column2: Veeva Message - Prevents downloading of certain objects to the iPad
column10:
This Veeva Message "TABLET_OBJECT_EXCLUDE_LIST" is causing data to not be downloaded to the iPad.

In Veeva CRM, 1 Veeva Message is active (one for category Ipad), but the Veeva Setting is pointing at category Tablet. Meaning this Veeva Message is not in use

In Vault CRM, 2 Veeva Message are active (one for category ipad and one for Tablet ), but the Veeva Messages have "_vod" values in them. Meaning that these Veeva Messages are not in use

In Migrated Vault CRM, 2 Veeva Message are active (one fore category iPad and one for Tablet), the Veeva Message in use has "__v" values in them. Probably Migrator translated it, causing the issue.

Zendesk ticket opened: https://veeva.zendesk.com/agent/tickets/1292885 . Pending fix: 243.0.10

statusMessage: Invalid Formula Expression for field [formula]
Customer: GSK

List of the 79 formula fields that error due to format which are not flagged in discovery

If the transformed formula from Migrator errors due to format, Migrator should create the formula field with a dummy formula rather than failing to create the field entirely. 

This will ensure that the formula field gets added to objects,layouts, PS, object types to avoid significant cascading manual fixes by services
column12:
GSK 79 formula fields fail cascading to page layouts, object types, permission set assignments etc. Significant rework

Script in progress to assign formula fields to Perm Sets but also need to assign to layouts and object types
column14:
Introduce two-step MDL creation process that will first create formula fields/validation rules with a default placeholder expression. In the second step, the expressions will be updated to their intended logic, or left as default if the expression is recognized as unsupported in Vault. This ensures that even expressions encountering errors during the load will still result in the successful creation of the fields, which will significantly improve the success rate for dependent metadata components.

Default expressions based on formula return type:

Text: "Function does not exist"
Number: 0
Currency: 0
Date: Date(1900, 1, 1)
Yes/No: false
DateTime: DateTimeValue("1900-01-01 00:00:00")
Time: Time(0,0,0)
Link: Hyperlink('https://veeva.com', 'Veeva', 'new_window')

[AK 01/21] Here is the analysis of other issues from the spreadsheet.

- Line 4: Conversion of `Account.Website` - Support for this field was added as part of VCRM-56250 in release 243.2.10.

- Lines 223684-223692 and 223708 - These are caused by the limitation of the library that's used for SOQL to VQL translation; they are reported in VCRM-61062. It's expected that the issue on the lines 223691-223693 will stay, as the complexity of the query exceeds the capability of the translator, but other issues are expected to get resolved.

- Lines 223694-223703, 223707, 223709 have been addressed in VCRM-58464 and it's targeted for release 24R3.4. Note - these records should be ignored, and after the fix they won't be migrated.

- Lines 223704-223705 - Does the migration project defines an override for the object `TOV_Event_Hospitality_Package__c`? If not, this custom object name can't be converted, so it's an expected message.

- Line 223706 - Incorrect data. The clause `WHERE (((Profile_vod_c = NULL) OR (Profile_vod_c = @@USER_PROFILE_ID@@))` is missing ')', as correctly stated in the error message.

- Line 223708 - Incorrect data. The clause `WHERE Account_vod_r.Name != null AND Inactive_vodc = FALSE` is invalid. It probably was intended to be `WHERE Name != null AND Inactive_vod_c = FALSE`

column2: Remove picklist dependencies that exceed 3 levels of hierarchy
column10:
GSK, Bayer and Novo all have picklist dependencies that go to 4-levels. Unless services removes one level of dependency in SFDC production, this will cause the fields to fail and cascades to Perm Sets, Page Layouts, ObjectTypes and results in missing data. 

The current workaround is not sustainable as it requires customers to agree to us removing dependency in prod out of office hours, running migrator, and then putting the dependency back before business hours start.

The simplest solution to the problem woud, seem to be adding a dependency between 2 PL fields to the ignore list so Migrator moves the field but does not hit the dependency limit

Profile to Permission Set recreate came back with a warning, however it doesnt seem to be related: value [spider_graph__c] for attribute [field] is invalid; value [child_record_type__c] for attribute [field] is invalid; value [ship_zip_4__c] for attribute [field] is invalid; value [grand_total_amount__c] for attribute [field] is invalid; value [gl_actual_cost_per_attendee__c] for attribute [field] is invalid; value [gl_go_online__c] for attribute [field] is invalid; value [gl_overspend__c] for attribute [field] is invalid; value [gl_total_actual_attendee_count__c] for attribute [field] is invalid; value [percentage_overspend__c] for attribute [field] is invalid

11/5: Searched logs which do not show any issues here - looks like a bug that is preventing permissions from sfdc profile being migrated to Vault PS but we cannot see the extent of the problem due to lack of error

JH 11/14 Additional Context: Upon digging into this further for Inhibrx, we are learning that this will be an issue across all customers. SFDC does not have the concept of Record Type OLS outside of create and it seems like the current version of Migrator does not take that consideration into account. Please see example:
-In Salesforce an Inhibrx Permission Set (INBRX ACCOUNT BASELINE) grants OLS R/E to the Account object and grants record type access to the Professional_vod and Institution_vod objects. What this means in Salesforce:
-User Assigned will be able to Create Accounts of record type Institution, and Professional (as long as they have C on a different PS or profile). User is able to see and edit all other Accounts of all record types, not just professional/institution
-In Vault CRM, the migrator creates the same INBRX ACCOUNT BASELINE permission set, but the OLS is set at the Record Type level, rather than the Object Type level. So they have R/E to Institution and Professional only.
-This means users assigned will only be able to Read/Edit those specific Record Types, any other Account with Record Type different than Professional/Institution they will not be able to see.
-The workaround is to grant r/e OLS to all other record types in Vault. This will need to be done across all objects that have record types.
-Ideal state would be to only grant create ols to the record type if a ps grants record type access in salesforce, if user gets R or E OLS, it should apply to all object types, to align with how salesforce works today

There are two parts to this issue:
1) Align is populating the 'Legacy MAID' instead of the actual one. This will be fixed in 4.40 release.
2) For Territory, another part of the issue depends on CRM. CRM has two fields: master_align_id_vod__c and master_align_id__v. column2: Picklist to text fields are not getting updated.
column10:
Source Vault ID: 7118
Target Vault ID: 254665
Vault Name:GSK Vault CRM Align ViiV TST
Migration ID: V6000000001X016
Data Extract: V64000000021148
Data Transform: V64000000020152
1st Data Load: V64000000021150
2nd Data Load: V64000000021201
Please note that I had to fix some of the data already due to project deadline.
In case of custom fields, which are picklist in CRM but Text in Align, the tool does not update the value on the align records.
I saw this issue when I was checking the Account Criteria records and atleast Accounts, Addresses and Product Metrics are impacted.
For example: Account's custom GSK Status picklist:
Label in Salesforce: Active      API name in Salesforce: Active        Value in Veeva Align's text field: Active             Value on the Rule Criteria record: Active
Label in Vault CRM: Active      API in Vault CRM: active__c              Value in Vault CRM Align's text field: Active      Value on the Rule Criteria record in Vault CRM Align: active__c
By this, the account not applies to the rule anymore and the related account-territory assignments will be end dated.
column14:
There are two issues with picklist-to-text mappings:

The rules contain field values as "abc__c", whereas the text field itself is migrated as "abc" (since Align does not currently perform any queries on field mapping; it simply migrates the field assuming it is a text field, which typically requires no conversion).
This will be fixed by first jira, ensuring that "__c" is appended to the "text" data - targeted for .21

In the rules, the conversion logic currently appends "_c" to all picklist values. However, there is no logic to determine whether the picklist in CRM contains "c" or "v" values. The issue here is that during the next CRM run, the data will be updated to "cdev", but the rules will still reference "cde_c", causing a mismatch.
This is a more significant issue and requires querying CRM metadata to determine which values use "_v" vs. "_c". When we fix this issue, the "__v" suffix should be added to both the "text" field and the "rule criteria" to ensure consistency - planned for 5.30

column14:
For RMT:

- This is fixed in the 5.10 release. The issue was caused because the "name__v" field on the RMT object (which is rosterid_territoryid) serves as the unique key for the object. Currently, this field is incorrectly populated with Legacy IDs. After the fix, the CRM push will no longer cause duplicates.
- As a short-term fix, the issue can be addressed immediately by manually updating the "name__v" field on the object

For MSP

MSP relies on IS2 records. If an IS2 record with the given Vault CRM Record ID does not exist in CRM, Align will attempt to create it again, which leads to duplicate records. Therefore, we should not delete IS2 records from the target instance unless they have a blank Vault CRM Record ID (which has also been fixed in version 4.40)

The Account Rule record's Account/Address/Parent HCO/Product Metric filter logic field holds the related Account Rule Critaria records' master align id and the operator between them. For example:
2d0a9a43-670e-4d2d-bf94-4eb4418fb160 AND 7401227b-b0db-4184-9293-95966109b7a4
These MAIDS are replaced during migration but as we see in the current system, the values are not replaced correctly. These maids are not legacy nor new maids of any criteria record.
What we can see from audit trail, it that the tool migrates the rules as is, than runs a process to update the Logic fields, however the MAIDs that the tool uses does not exists in any of the systems.
The issue still persists after yesterday's rerun of data etl.
column12: These rules can not function properly, which means that they end date all rule based assignments and generate none.
column14:
- Adding account_rule_criteria_history__aln and
account_rule_history__aln to the configuration ignore list. This should fix the issue (and confirm on the GChat that all are okay to proceed

column2: Picklist values in Channel Criteria: discrepancy between Vault CRM and Align
column10:
Align stores picklist value labels in the channel_criteria__aln field, when a record referencing a picklist field is created via the UI. Example:
sent_email__v.sent_email_status__v:::eq:::Delivered,,Sent

However, Vault CRM stores the API names when the record is created via the UI, or when the record is migrated from Veeva CRM:
sent_email__v.sent_email_status__v:::eq:::sent__v,,delivered__v

When the record is pushed from Align, the Align version appears in CRM but the labels do not work in the MCCP calculation (we tested this). It seems the calculation expects the CRM version so Align should push the API names.
column12: Align-managed MCCPs do not work with the MCCP calculation.

column2: CRM data ingest behavior when pushing to picklist fields from Align: labels rejected, as opposed to loading via Loader.
column10:
Push MCCPs to CRM error:

mc_cycle_channel__v Failed to upsert. Reason: INVALID_DATA: Invalid value [F2F] specified for parameter [bph_global_channel__c] : Picklist [mc_cycle_channel_bph_global_channel__c] does not contain [F2F]

In Align, the mc_cycle_channel__aln.bph_global_channel__c custom field has the value F2F which matches the picklist value label of the corresponding value in CRM ('F2F'=>'f2f__c'). However, CRM does not "accept" the value 'F2F' during the push process. I assume it expects the picklist value name 'f2f__c'.

This behavior is different from the Vault Loader behavior where the system recognizes and accepts 'F2F' as a valid value for the picklist (I've tested it and Vault Help also states this - see auto-formatting).

https://platform.veevavault.help/en/lr/26607/#auto-formatting

Question: can you confirm the behavior during the push process is expected? If yes, then we need to do some adjustment e.g. change the text field in Align to a picklist.
column11: Not a migrator issue, more of a Vault platform question.
column12:
MCCPs not getting pushed to CRM.

We can circumvent this limitation by removing the field from the outbound mapping which enables us to continue testing but this is not a solution for production.
column14:
This is expected behavior. The data stored in the backend always corresponds to the API names; hence, the text field data must match the API name in the CRM to successfully push the data.

I agreethis would be a good time to consider converting this field into a picklist as well

- Discrepancies between the user__sys file generated from CRM and what Align expects. As a result, the Record ID was not populated, causing an error during the push
 - The issue has been fixed and tested for a .20 release
- There is another related known issue: https://jira.veevadev.com/browse/VCRM-66416. Only caused when a master_align_id_vod__C is mapped to master_align_id__aln on Parent HCO   (caused by CRM issue - https://jira.veevadev.com/browse/VCRM-58674)

- Identified the issue, Vault CRM migrations do not transfer ObjectTerritory2Association objects to account_territory_v if they have 'Master_Align_Id_vod_c' set. As a result, we cannot populate the Vault CRM Record ID for these records. The short-term approach is to delete these IS2 records that are missing Vault CRM Record IDs, which should resolve the issue with the push to CRM. This is NOT A BLOCKER
- Tracking Jira for a longer term fix. This will ensure we only migrate IS2 records for which counterparts exist in CRM, and hence no failures during push due to blank Vault CRM Record IDs - planned for 4.40 release (on 6th March)

column14:
Update: This was addressed in v243.4.10. Reran the Data ETL manually on migration V6000000001V012 after updating the migration version. This is ready to test

[PREV NOTES] - Migration introduced a bug during the push due to how it migrates IS2 records. The Account Territory push queries IS2 records to determine what AT records have already been pushed by finding the Vault CRM Record IDs and using those IDs for various comparisons. Currently we are missing the step to stamp the new Vault CRM Record Id from Vault CRM on the IS2 which is needed for the job to stop aborting.

We are working to fix the bug. I am coordinating with sustaining engineering on the fix, which I suspect is a combination of pulling the two files, territory from VCRM and IS2 from Vault CRM Align and manually setting the IS2 Vault CRM Record IDs

column2: Over Reached Threshold and Under Reached Threshold validation and discrepancy vs. CRM
column10:
Align has a validation to ensure: "The value of Under Reached Threshold must be lower than or equal to the value of Over Reached Threshold."
Both fields allow values between 0-99 in Align while in CRM they can be between -99 and +99.
Taking an example where we want to set under reached to -10% and over reached to +5%: this means we need to set Under Reached Threshold=10 and Over Reached Threshold=5 which is blocked by the Align validation while it is allowed in CRM and it seems to be a valid business case.
I think we shouldn't have this validation for the 2 fields, but they should be independent. NB, this has been a long-standing behavior in Align but it is misleading and blocks certain pairs of values. I can set for example 10-10 in the two fields, or 5-10, but not 10-5 as shown in the above example.
I think the confusion comes from two similar Align fields: Upper Utilization Threshold and Lower Utilization Threshold where the values in the fields represent the "absolute" boundaries of the acceptable range in percentages (i.e. utilization must be between 95 and 115% of the capacity), while the values in the under/over reached threshold fields represent the deviation from the baseline 100% (e.g. (-)10% and (+)5%). It makes sense to have such a validation in the former case but not in the latter.

column2: Veeva CRM lookup fields which have lookup filter filtering on Account IDs are creating duplicate fields in Vault CRM.
column10:
Customer: Bayer (GDV org)
Job ID: V60000000029006
Vault ID: 262911

Veeva CRM lookup fields which have lookup filter filtering on Account IDs are creating duplicate fields in Vault CRM.

Example:

In Veeva CRM we have:
BPH_Opportunity_Line_Item__c.BPH_Ship_To__c 
-> Lookup field to Account_vod__c object

BPH_Opportunity_Line_Item__c.BPH_Address__c 
-> Lookup field to Address_vod__c object
-> with lookup filter "Opportunity Line Item: Ship To ID equals Address: Account ID" (meaning only Addresses linked to Account added to Ship To field can be selected in Address for the Opportunity Line record).

After migration in Vault CRM we have:
bph_opportunity_line_item__c.bph_ship_to__c
-> Object field to Account__v object

bph_opportunity_line_item__c.ctrl_account__c
-> Controlling field for bph_opportunity_line_item__c.bph_address__c
-> Object field to Account__v object

bph_opportunity_line_item__c.bph_address__c
-> Object field to addres__v object
-> Controlled by field bph_opportunity_line_item__c.ctrl_account__c

It should have been: 
-> bph_opportunity_line_item__c.bph_address__c field controlled by bph_opportunity_line_item__c.bph_ship_to__c field
Or
-> bph_opportunity_line_item__c.bph_address__c with a VQL criteria to filter for "bph_address__c.account__v = bph_ship_to__c"

Screenshots here - https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1Ts9xy9ogf34PIG5s2fSXfb1KoGjxJqzp
column12:
4 duplicated fields created.

At the moment end-users will have to populate 2 fields with the same value any time they are creating a record. + poor UX.

column2: Translation of Page Layout sections (Related lists) missing
column10:
When Migrating translations for Page Layouts, the translation of related list are not carried over, and they are not indicated in the logs either.

My assumption is because of platform difference that is not accounted for:
1. In Salesforce, related lists translations are based on the Object Name/Tab translation by default and can be additionally translated on the object level (e.g. how the Call related list should be translated across any layouts for the Account object) 

2. In Vault CRM, each layout section (incl. related lists) can be individually translated. Migrator does not account for these, meaning that on all layouts the related list labels are all in English

This is causing a significant amount of translation work, between extracting from Salesforce, transforming it to Vault Translation file format, Loading translations. Especially because in Vault the translation of the related list needs to be specified on each layout that the related list is used on (in salesforce it is defined on the object level)

Job Id: 9cdf5c37-3dc2-4223-a

Help Content can be fixed via Translation files and excel work for all languages
column13: Swedish Orphan Biovitrum, Otsuka Europe, Novo US
column14:
[AK 05/29] Vault platform limitation: it is not possible to clear the standard field help text in vault using mdl (see DEV-802688)
As a workaround, for cases when there is no help content in salesforce, instead of setting the vault help content to null or empty string (which could edit: not clear the standard field help text), we set the help content in vault as a single whitespace character in the mdl. That way, we can make the help content look like it got cleared by replacing it with a space character. It is not actually cleared, but it looks like it is cleared in the ui, so approximates the desired behavior.
This workaround looks fine in the ui for web browser, however for the ipad it clutters the ui with extra help icons
The concern about the extra help icons cluttering the ui in the ipad was raised up at the time
PM decision was to go ahead with the workaround even if it may cause extra help icons for the ipad

[AK 06/02] After discussion with services, the decision is to preserve the value from Vault CRM template instead of tryint to nullify the field using space character.

column2: a lookup field inside a Formula do not migrate
Overrides for SFDC Long text fields that are 32,768
column10:
No job ID - all customers impacted

Long text field default in SFDC is 32,768 but the limit in Vault is 32,000. Currently we have been making these attachment fields which is NOT ideal for customers as the text will fit in 32,000.
Migrator is set to flag these and services is looking at tooling to potentially update them in SFDC but not all customers can do that without it taking months.

Request is for migrator tool to allow us to override the field types.
Option 1 (preferred): Migrator will automatically shorten the fields that are 32,768 to 32,000 and leave the fields as long text.  We would then add overrides for any fields that we ACTUALLY want to become attachment fields
Option 2: Migrator will automatically convert those fields to attachment fields and services will add to the overrides the individual fields where we want them truncated to 32,000 and to remain long text

31 May: Mike Pay is building a tool to analyse SFDC for fields that are 32,768 and check if any records would be truncated should the field be reduced to 32,000 characters. The output of this tool should be a csv of overrides to load into Migrator that override the field length for the field to 32,000 characters. Nastya to confirm that field length override will be possible and what the syntax should be. NOTE: whilst Pavi's script worked ok on small orgs, they fail when tested on large data sets (e.g. BI Child 1 org). Mike needs to bulkify the approach before we can publish on the tools portal - challenging given the SFDC api's so will take time.

column2: account_territory__v records migrated with manual__v and rule__v both set to True on a record
column10:
Job ID: 9ab98ee4-c280-49ec-a
Customer: Sobi

There are approximately 6000 account_territory__v records where both rule and manual flags are set to true. My understanding is that in Vault a record should have either rule (in case of assignment rule) or manual (in case of data load or ATL record) set to true. I can see that for example the Account (001QD00000ZX5uSYAT) has two records (one for Territory2AssignmentRule and one for Territory2Manual in Veeva CRM) for the Territory (0MIQD00000001Ab4AI)

Wondering if this transformation of setting both flags to true is correct in Vault CRM according to product specifications. As in this case we cannot understand why the assignment happened to the Account.
column14: [06/30] This is the way it was designed: In SFDC, there can be two different ObjectTerritory2Association records for the same account and territory (which we will call twin records), one with AssociationCause = manual and one with AssociationCause = rule. Our transformation logic, per VCRM-22312, is supposed to combine these two into one record in Vault with manual__v = true and rule__v = true.

column2: Data ETL failures due to missing metadata not flagged in loading status or mapping logs
column10:
Customer: BI, Job ID for Metadata ETL: 4bbc167d-af09-46c2-a job ID for Data Loading: 
6c55d0b8-7acb-4d07-8

BI getting data failures across Product due to missing picklist values in Vault CRM (e.g. "Error Type INVALID_DATA Invalid value [ea__c] specified for parameter [inventory_order_uom__v] : Picklist [product_inventory_order_uom__v] does not contain [ea__c]"). 

The picklist values causing the errors seem not to have been picked up by Migrator as they do not appear in the Mapping file or error logs. It looks like there is a bug in Migrator somewhere during the Metadata ETL leading to us missing multiple picklist values from multiple fields.

7/9: Per conversation wtih Nastya, looks like the root cause (still being confirmed) is that Migrator attempted to load data for inactive picklist values. The mapping file would not have shown these inactive values, and Migrator would not see them either. When attempting to load these values, the MDL failed. Need to understand from devs why this has only come up with BI and not on other migrations. There may be a solution where the Dev team can provide us with an MDL that may resolve these errors--TBD.

column2: Migrated user_territory__v records have the external_id__v field blank

Update June 26 - Sandor: similar situation is happening with account_territory__v records where migrator is not populating the external_id__v records, which is causing that at the next territory assignment run the system is creating duplicate account_territory records
column12:
Possibility of creating duplicate user_territory__v records.

column2: Layout Profiles Exclude Event Related Objects
column10:
Customer: ALL
Job ID: N/A

For Events Management, page layout assignment is controlled by the Page Layout Engine which is defined on the Event Configuration record for each Events object type in the Event Layout section. When a Layout Profile with layouts specific to these same objects controlled by the Page Layout Engine (em_attendee__v, em_event__v, em_event_budget__v, em_event_material__v, em_event_session__v, em_event_session_attendee__v, em_event_speaker__v, em_event_team_member__v, em_expense_estimate__v, expense_header__v, expense_line__v), then it conflicts with the assignment from the page layout engine and the user is no longer able to see the right page layout for their Event.

With the migrator, it creates a layout profile for all objects with greater than one page layout, we need to also exclude all objects mentioned above that are controlled by the Page Layout Engine. Otherwise, every migration for a customer that has Events Management we are spending time removing these obejcts from the Layout Profiles.
column12: This issue is effecting all the objects mentioned in column J. Currently, the manual workaround is to delete all these objects from all layout profiles that have been created by the migrator.

column2: VMOCs with an 'OR' operator for different objects in a WHERE clause should be split
column10: No specific Job ID - affects all customers. Vault does not allow VMOCs with an OR operator for multiple objects resulting in serrvices having to manually split certain VMOCs Migrator migrates. Please enhance Migrator logic to perform the split.
column14:
[AK 11/4] Development investigated this and the conclusion is that this need human intervention rather than a bling splitting. Example:

The error:

WHERE ((Account_vod__r.Name != null OR User_vod__c = @@VOD_SF_USER_ID@@ OR Coach_vod__c = @@VOD_SF_USER_ID@@ OR OwnerId = @@VOD_SF_USER_ID@@) AND Status_vod__c != 'Development_vod' AND Start_Date_vod__c <= TODAY)
this is a real query that connects multiple different relationship chain with ORs.

However, there is a standard mapping that maps below Soql to the Vql:

WHERE OwnerId = @@VOD_SF_USER_ID@@ AND Account_vod__r.Name != null AND Status_vod__c != 'Development_vod' AND Start_Date_vod__c <= TODAY
to

WHERE VCRM_FIELD{this:OwnerId} = @@USER_ID@@ AND VCRM_FIELD{this:Account_vod__c} IN (SELECT id FROM VCRM_OUTBOUND{this:Account_vod__c}) AND VCRM_FIELD{this:Status_vod__c} != 'development__v' AND VCRM_FIELD{this:Start_Date_vod__c} <= TODAY
The key is that even if we apply a generic solution to seperate such VMOC to multiple ones, the ending result (multuple VMOCs) may not be the ideal one that is offered in the standard mapping.

column2: TSF records linked to incorrect accounts
column10:
There were TSFs migrated to Vault CRM linked to incorrect accounts. As an initial analysis we identified that the possible cause is that the TSF records in Veeva CRM are assigned to wrong addresses in the 'Preferred Address' relationship, so the migrator might have consider the account related to the preferred address instead of the actual TSF related account.
As an example: The TSF "Territory-A" is linked to the account "Dr. John", however, this TSF address (Preferred Address lookup) has an address that belongs to "Dr. Michael". The same TSF for the "Territory-A" is now in Vault CRM associated to "Dr. Michael" and not to "Dr. John" as it should be.

Migrator 1st data ETL job URL

Migrator 2nd data ETL job URL

Migrator 3rd data ETL job URL
column12: The workaround is to re-create all those TSFs with the correct account and then let the incorrect ones blank.
column14:
[AK 11/13] 
The the cause mentioned in the description could be possible because of the controlling field. In the vault side, the "account_v" field is the controlling field of "address_v". Therefore, to make sure the controlling dependency work, we will set the account according to what the address pointing to. 

Some details in the case, we extract these fields from SFDC: "Account_vod_c, Address_vodc, Address_vodr.Account_vod_c".

According to the rules in VCRM-13725: the controlling field value should be set based on the child/controlled relationship to the parent. Therefore, if there is a value from "Address_vod_r.Account_vod_c", we will prioritize the value when setting for the account. This is to make sure we can load the data without any controlling dependency issues.

So the cause mentioned in the description could be possible. If they are assigned to wrong addresses, the migrator will set the account which the address points to, instead of the actual TSF account. 

A way to fix is they correct the data to the right addresses, and migrator can run the delta.

column12: impacting 92744 account records
column14:
[AK 12/10] The issue is that the data model has a reference to the address which makes us create a controlling field for it (Account), when data comes in we are populating it with the parent account id for that address which means self-referencing for the record as that address is a child of that account. The only path forward I see is to ignore the address reference field. 

Example: Account id = 1 has multiple addresses (children ids 11, 12, 13). 11 is the one that customer wants to reference on account id 1, this means controlling field will have to be set to id =1, we get an error: record cannot reference itself;
